entry.et: Middle English privat, from Anglo-French, from Latin privatus, from past participle of privare to deprive, release, from privus private, individual; probably akin to Latin pro for, in front of for

def.dt: :intended for or restricted to the use of a particular person, group, or class a private park
:belonging to or concerning an individual person, company, or interest a private house
:restricted to the individual or arising independently of others private opinion
:carried on by the individual independently of the usual institutions a doctor in private practice
:being educated by independent study or a tutor or in a private school private students
:not general in effect a private statute
:of, relating to, or receiving hospital service in which the patient has more privileges than a semiprivate or ward patient
:not holding public office or employment a private citizen
:not related to one's official position :personal private correspondence
:being a private
:withdrawn from company or observation a private retreat
:not known or intended to be known publicly :secret
:preferring to keep personal affairs to oneself :valuing privacy highly
:unsuitable for public use or display
:not having shares that can be freely traded on the open market a private company
:one not in public office
:privacy
:private parts
:a person of low rank in various organizations (as a police or fire department)
:an enlisted man of the lowest rank in the marine corps or of one of the two lowest ranks in the army
:not openly or in public
:private investigator
:free enterprise
:private investigator
:an enlisted man ranking in the army above a private and below a corporal and in the marine corps above a private and below a lance corporal
:a person not a member of a police force who is licensed to do detective work (as investigation of suspected wrongdoing or searching for missing persons)
:a label associated with a specific chain store
:a brand or product having a private label usually hyphenated when used attributively private-label clothes
:a branch of law concerned with private persons, property, and relationships compare public law
:the external genital and excretory organs
